                            <h1>
                            &ldquo;A Teacher Come from God&rdquo;
                            </h1>
                            <h2 class="author">
                                    <a href="http://lds.org/church/leader/jeffrey-r-holland?lang=eng"><div class="byline" id="">
				<p uri="/ensign/1998/05/a-teacher-come-from-god.p2" class="">Elder Jeffrey R. Holland</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1998/05/a-teacher-come-from-god.p" class="">Of the Quorum of the Twelve Apostles</p>
			</div></a>   
                                    </h2>
                            <hr>
                        </div><!-- end #details -->
                       
                        <div id="primary">
                            
                            
                            <blockquote class="intro dontHighlight">
                                        <a href="http://lds.org/church/leader/jeffrey-r-holland?lang=eng">
                                                        <img id="talkPhoto" src="/bc/content/shared/content/images/leaders/jeffrey-r-holland-10.jpg" alt="Jeffrey R. Holland" class="img-decor">
                                                    </a>
                                        
                                        <div class="kicker" id="">We must revitalize and reenthrone superior teaching in the Church&mdash;at home, from the pulpit, in our administrative meetings, and surely in the classroom.</div>
                                        
                                    </blockquote>
                            
                            <span style="display: none" id="article-id">98905_000_013</span>
			<div class="figure">
				
			</div>
			<p uri="/ensign/1998/05/a-teacher-come-from-god.p4" class="">When Nicodemus came to Jesus early in the Savior&rsquo;s ministry, he spoke for all of us when he said, &ldquo;Rabbi, we know that thou art a teacher come from God.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	<a href="#footnote1-98905_000_013">1</a>
      </sup></p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1998/05/a-teacher-come-from-god.p5" class=""><a class="no-link-style" href="http://jesuschrist.lds.org/">Christ</a> was, of course, much more than a teacher. He was the very Son of God, the Holy One of the eternal gospel plan, the Savior and Redeemer of the world.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1998/05/a-teacher-come-from-god.p6" class="">But Nicodemus was starting about the way you and I started, the way any child or young student or new convert begins&mdash;by recognizing and responding to a thrilling teacher who touches the innermost feelings of our heart.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1998/05/a-teacher-come-from-god.p7" class="">In recent months President Gordon B. Hinckley has called on us to hold our people close to the Church, especially the newly converted member. In issuing this call President Hinckley has reminded that we all need at least three things to remain firmly in the faith&mdash;a friend, a responsibility, and &ldquo;[nourishing] by the good word of God.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	<a href="#footnote2-98905_000_013">2</a>
      </sup></p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1998/05/a-teacher-come-from-god.p8" class="">Inspired instruction in the home and in the Church helps provide this crucial element of nourishing by the good word of God. We are <span class="emphasis">so</span> grateful to all who teach. We love you and appreciate you more than we can say. We have great confidence in you. To teach effectively and to feel you are succeeding is demanding work indeed. But it is worth it. We can receive &ldquo;no greater call.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	<a href="#footnote3-98905_000_013">3</a>
      </sup> Surely the opportunity to magnify that call exists everywhere. The need for it is everlasting. Fathers, mothers, siblings, friends, missionaries, home and visiting teachers, priesthood and auxiliary leaders, classroom instructors&mdash;each is, in his or her own way, &ldquo;come from God&rdquo; for our schooling and our salvation. In this Church it is virtually impossible to find anyone who is <span class="emphasis">not</span> a guide of one kind or another to his or her fellow members of the flock. Little wonder that Paul would say in his writings, &ldquo;God hath set some in the church, first apostles, secondarily prophets, thirdly teachers.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	<a href="#footnote4-98905_000_013">4</a>
      </sup></p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1998/05/a-teacher-come-from-god.p9" class="">For each of us to &ldquo;come unto Christ,&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	<a href="#footnote5-98905_000_013">5</a>
      </sup> to keep His commandments and follow His example back to the Father is surely the highest and holiest purpose of human existence. To help others do that as well&mdash;to teach, persuade, and prayerfully lead them to walk that path of redemption also&mdash;surely that must be the second most significant task in our lives. Perhaps that is why President David O. McKay once said, &ldquo;No greater responsibility can rest upon any man [or woman] than to be a teacher of God&rsquo;s children.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	<a href="#footnote6-98905_000_013">6</a>
      </sup> We are, in fact, all somewhat like the man of Ethiopia to whom Philip was sent. Like him, we may know enough to reach out for religion. We may invest ourselves in the scriptures. We may even give up our earthly treasures, but without sufficient instruction we may miss the meaning of all this and the requirements that still lie before us. So we cry with this man of great authority, &ldquo;How can [we understand,] except some [teacher] should guide [us]?&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	<a href="#footnote7-98905_000_013">7</a>
      </sup></p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1998/05/a-teacher-come-from-god.p10" class="">The Apostle Paul taught: &ldquo;For whosoever shall call upon the name of the Lord shall be saved.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1998/05/a-teacher-come-from-god.p11" class="">&ldquo;[But] how then shall they call on him in whom they have not believed? and how shall they believe in him of whom they have not heard?</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1998/05/a-teacher-come-from-god.p12" class="">&ldquo;<span class="emphasis">Faith cometh by hearing,</span> and hearing by the word of God.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	<a href="#footnote8-98905_000_013">8</a>
      </sup></p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1998/05/a-teacher-come-from-god.p13" class="">Now, at a time when our prophet is calling for more faith through hearing the word of God, we must revitalize and reenthrone superior teaching in the Church&mdash;at home, from the pulpit, in our administrative meetings, and surely in the classroom. Inspired teaching must never become a lost art in the Church, and we must make certain our quest for it does not become a lost tradition.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1998/05/a-teacher-come-from-god.p14" class="">President Spencer W. Kimball once pled: &ldquo;Stake presidents, bishops, and branch presidents, please take a particular interest in improving the quality of teaching in the Church. &hellip; I fear,&rdquo; he said, &ldquo;that all too often many of our members come to church, sit through a class or a meeting, and &hellip; then return home having been largely [uninspired]. It is especially unfortunate when this happens at a time &hellip; of stress, temptation, or crisis [in their life]. We all need to be touched and nurtured by the Spirit,&rdquo; he said, &ldquo;and <span class="emphasis">effective teaching</span> is one of the most important ways this can happen. We often do vigorous work,&rdquo; President Kimball concluded, &ldquo;to get members to come to Church but then do not adequately watch over what they receive when they do come.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	<a href="#footnote9-98905_000_013">9</a>
      </sup> On this subject President Hinckley himself has said, <span class="emphasis">&ldquo;Effective teaching is the very essence of leadership in the Church.&rdquo;</span> May I repeat that. &ldquo;Effective teaching is the very essence of leadership in the Church. Eternal life,&rdquo; President Hinckley continued, &ldquo;will come only as men and women are <span class="emphasis">taught with such effectiveness</span> that they change and discipline their lives. They cannot be coerced into righteousness or into heaven. They must be led, and that means teaching.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	<a href="#footnote10-98905_000_013">10</a>
      </sup></p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1998/05/a-teacher-come-from-god.p15" class="">Among the last words the Savior said to His disciples and among the first words He says to us today are: &ldquo;Go ye therefore, and teach all nations. &hellip; [Teach] them to observe all things whatsoever I have commanded you: and, lo, I am with you [always], even unto the end of the world.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	<a href="#footnote11-98905_000_013">11</a>
      </sup> To Peter, the apostolic leader of the Church, the resurrected and ascending Christ said, &ldquo;Feed my lambs, &hellip; feed my sheep, &hellip; follow [thou] me.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	<a href="#footnote12-98905_000_013">12</a>
      </sup></p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1998/05/a-teacher-come-from-god.p16" class="">In all of this we must remember that the Lord has never given more emphatic counsel to the Church than that we are to teach the gospel &ldquo;by the Spirit, even the Comforter which was sent forth to teach the truth.&rdquo;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1998/05/a-teacher-come-from-god.p17" class="">Do we teach the gospel &ldquo;by the Spirit of truth?&rdquo; He has inquired. Or do we teach it &ldquo;some other way? And if it be by some other way,&rdquo; He warns, &ldquo;it is not of God.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	<a href="#footnote13-98905_000_013">13</a>
      </sup> In language echoing other commandments, He has said, &ldquo;If ye receive not the Spirit ye shall not teach.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	<a href="#footnote14-98905_000_013">14</a>
      </sup></p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1998/05/a-teacher-come-from-god.p18" class="">No eternal learning can take place without that quickening of the Spirit from heaven. So, parents, teachers, and leaders, we must face our tasks the way <a class="no-link-style" href="http://lds.org/ensign/1998/04/moses-witness-of-jesus-christ?lang=eng">Moses</a> faced the promised land. Knowing he could not succeed any other way, Moses said to Jehovah, &ldquo;If thy presence go not with me, carry us not up hence.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	<a href="#footnote15-98905_000_013">15</a>
      </sup></p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1998/05/a-teacher-come-from-god.p19" class="">That is what our members really want when they gather in a meeting or come into a classroom anyway. Most people don&rsquo;t come to church looking merely for a few new gospel facts or to see old friends, though all of that is important. They come seeking a spiritual experience. They want peace. They want their faith fortified and their hope renewed. They want, in short, to be nourished by the good word of God [see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/moro/6.4?lang=eng#3" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Moro. 6:4</a>], to be strengthened by the powers of heaven. Those of us who are called upon to speak or teach or lead have an obligation to help provide that, as best we possibly can. We can only do that if we ourselves are striving to know God, if we ourselves are continually seeking the light of His Only Begotten Son. Then, if our hearts are right, if we are as clean as we can be, if we have prayed and wept and prepared and worried until we don&rsquo;t know what more we can do, God can say to us as He did to Alma and the sons of Mosiah: &ldquo;Lift up thy head and rejoice. &hellip; I will give unto you success.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	<a href="#footnote16-98905_000_013">16</a>
      </sup></p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1998/05/a-teacher-come-from-god.p20" class="">We do have a legitimate worry about the new member, wanting each one to stay with us and enjoy the full blessings of the Church. I am just simple enough to think that if we continue to <span class="emphasis">teach them</span>&mdash;with the same Christlike spirit, conviction, doctrine, and personal interest the missionaries have shown them&mdash;new converts will not only stay with us but, quite literally, could not be kept away. The need for continuing such solid teaching is obvious. In times like ours we <span class="emphasis">all</span> need what Mormon called &ldquo;the virtue of the word of God&rdquo; because, he said, it &ldquo;had [a] more powerful effect upon the minds of the people than the sword, or anything else, which had happened unto them.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	<a href="#footnote17-98905_000_013">17</a>
      </sup> When crises come in our lives&mdash;and they will&mdash;the philosophies of men interlaced with a few scriptures and poems just won&rsquo;t do. Are we really nurturing our youth and our new members in a way that will sustain them when the stresses of life appear? Or are we giving them a kind of theological Twinkie&mdash;spiritually empty calories? President John Taylor once called such teaching &ldquo;fried froth,&rdquo; the kind of thing you could eat all day and yet finish feeling totally unsatisfied.<sup class="noteMarker">
	<a href="#footnote18-98905_000_013">18</a>
      </sup> During a severe winter several years ago, President <a href="http://lds.org/church/leader/boyd-k-packer?lang=eng">Boyd K. Packer</a> noted that a goodly number of deer had died of starvation while their stomachs were full of hay. In an honest effort to assist, agencies had supplied the superficial when the substantial was what had been needed. Regrettably they had <span class="emphasis">fed</span> the deer but they had not <span class="emphasis">nourished</span> them.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1998/05/a-teacher-come-from-god.p21" class="">I love what President J. Reuben Clark said of our youth well over a half century ago. The same thing can be said of new members. &ldquo;[They] are hungry for the things of the spirit,&rdquo; he said; &ldquo;they are eager to learn the Gospel, and they want it straight, undiluted. &hellip;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1998/05/a-teacher-come-from-god.p22" class="">&ldquo;&hellip; You do not have to sneak up behind [them] and whisper religion in [their] ears; &hellip; you can bring these truths [out] openly.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	<a href="#footnote19-98905_000_013">19</a>
      </sup></p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1998/05/a-teacher-come-from-god.p23" class="">Satan is certainly not subtle in his teachings; why should we be? Whether we are instructing our children at home or standing before an audience in church, let us <span class="emphasis">never</span> make our faith difficult to detect. Remember&mdash;we are to be teachers &ldquo;come from God.&rdquo; Never sow seeds of doubt. Avoid self-serving performance and vanity. Prepare lessons well. Give scripturally based sermons. Teach the revealed doctrine. Bear heartfelt testimony. Pray and practice and try to improve. In our administrative meetings let us both &ldquo;instruct and edify&rdquo; as the revelations say, that even in these our teaching may ultimately be &ldquo;from on high.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	<a href="#footnote20-98905_000_013">20</a>
      </sup> The Church will be the better for it, and so will you, for as Paul said to the Romans, &ldquo;Thou therefore which teachest another, teachest thou not thyself?&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	<a href="#footnote21-98905_000_013">21</a>
      </sup></p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1998/05/a-teacher-come-from-god.p24" class="">A memorable account of the power of such teaching comes from the life of the prophet Jeremiah. This great man felt the way most teachers or speakers or Church officers feel when called&mdash;inexperienced, inadequate, frightened. &ldquo;Ah, Lord,&rdquo; he cried, &ldquo;behold, I cannot speak: for I am [but] a child.&rdquo;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1998/05/a-teacher-come-from-god.p25" class="">But the Lord reassured him: &ldquo;Be not afraid of their faces: for I am with thee. &hellip; Therefore gird up thy loins, and arise, and speak unto them.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	<a href="#footnote22-98905_000_013">22</a>
      </sup></p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1998/05/a-teacher-come-from-god.p26" class="">So speak unto them he did, but initially not with much success. Things went from bad to worse until finally he was imprisoned and made a laughingstock among the people. Angry that he had been so mistreated and maligned, Jeremiah vowed, in effect, never to teach another lesson, whether that be to an investigator, Primary child, new convert, or&mdash;heaven forbid&mdash;the 15-year-olds. &ldquo;I will not make mention of [the Lord], nor speak any more in his name,&rdquo; the discouraged prophet said. But then came the turning point of Jeremiah&rsquo;s life. Something had been happening with every testimony he had borne, every scripture he had read, every truth he had taught. Something had been happening that he hadn&rsquo;t counted on. Even as he vowed to close his mouth and walk away from the Lord&rsquo;s work, he found that he could not. Why? Because &ldquo;his word was in mine heart as a burning fire shut up in my bones, and I was weary with forbearing, and I could not stay.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	<a href="#footnote23-98905_000_013">23</a>
      </sup></p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1998/05/a-teacher-come-from-god.p27" class="">That is what happens in the gospel to both the teacher and the taught. It is what happened to Nephi and Lehi when, the book of Helaman says, &ldquo;the Holy Spirit of God did come down from heaven, and did enter into their hearts, and they were filled as if with fire, and they could speak forth marvelous words.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	<a href="#footnote24-98905_000_013">24</a>
      </sup> Surely it must have been that kind of heavenly joy Mary Magdalene experienced when near the Garden Tomb she unexpectedly beheld her beloved resurrected Lord and said to Him simply, &ldquo;Rabboni,&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	<a href="#footnote25-98905_000_013">25</a>
      </sup> which is to say, literally, &ldquo;Teacher.&rdquo;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1998/05/a-teacher-come-from-god.p28" class="">From all of us who have been taught to all of you who teach&mdash;we say thank you, from the bottom of our hearts. May we exalt the teaching experience within the home and within the Church and improve our every effort to edify and instruct. In all of our meetings and all of our messages may we nourish by the good word of God. And may our children and new converts, our neighbors and new friends, say of our honest efforts, &ldquo;Thou art a teacher come from God.&rdquo; [<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/john/3.2?lang=eng#2" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">John 3:2</a>.]  In the sacred name of the Master Teacher, <a class="no-link-style" href="http://mormon.org/jesus-christ">Jesus Christ</a>, amen.</p>
		
                            
                            
